threat_severity.level_description: Severity MEDIUM because it was considered trojan.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit MSB executable, MIPS, MIPS-I version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, not stripped

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: Detects suspicious single byte XORed keyword 'Mozilla/5.0' - it uses yara's XOR modifier and therefore cannot print the XOR key. You can use the CyberChef recipe linked in the reference field to brute force the used key.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: Florian Roth

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a Mirai-based botnet variant designed for IoT environments. It exhibits typical malware behaviors including process name spoofing (renaming itself to /bin/busybox), disabling hardware watchdogs to prevent system reboots, and ensuring a single instance by binding to a specific port (55581). It contains multiple DDoS attack modules (TCP SYN, ACK, STOMP, UDP plain, and VSE) and implements a process killer ('pkiller' and 'locker' functions) that scans /proc to terminate competing malware or diagnostic tools. It communicates with a hardcoded C2 server at 102.200.5.10 on port 24.
